{"type":"message-part","timestamp":"2026-06-13T17:48:25.414Z","messageId":"568794b6-2e66-45c6-8cf8-45cf5e89fc84","role":"assistant","index":21,"part":{"type":"reasoning","text":"**Aggregating Features**\n\nMy current focus is on how to best aggregate temporal features. I'm investigating the concatenation of mean and standard deviation over time for various librosa feature families, aiming for a single 1-D vector per audio file.\n\n**Refining Feature Extraction**\n\nI'm clarifying the feature aggregation process. Specifically, I'll compute the temporal mean and standard deviation for each individual feature family (MFCCs, spectral contrast, zero crossing rate, spectral centroid) and then concatenate these resulting vectors. This ensures a consistent 1-D feature representation per audio file.\n\n**Validating Feature Order**\n\nI'm confirming that the order of concatenating the aggregated features (means and standard deviations for MFCCs, spectral contrast, ZCR, and spectral centroid) is consistent across all audio files. This ensures a reproducible 1-D feature representation for each sample.\n\n**Implementing Feature Extraction**\n\nMy thoughts are now on execution. I'm writing the Python code to extract the aggregated features from the training and testing files. I will train a logistic regression model using the training data and then use it to predict labels for the testing files. I've confirmed the structure of the training and testing datasets.\n\n**Automating Predictions**\n\nMy current focus is on automating the prediction process. I'm refining the script to dynamically locate all `.wav` files within the test directory, predict their labels, and systematically write these predictions to a CSV file, ensuring correct formatting and inclusion of only basenames.\n\n","state":"done"}}
{"type":"message-part","timestamp":"2026-06-13T17:48:25.527Z","messageId":"568794b6-2e66-45c6-8cf8-45cf5e89fc84","role":"assistant","index":22,"part":{"type":"tool-writeToFile","toolCallId":"CoJVI63GUqI84sUd","state":"output-available","input":{"path":"/workspace/classify.py","content":"import os\nimport glob\nimport numpy as np\nimport librosa\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\n\ndef extract_features(file_path):\n    print(f\"Extracting features from: {file_path}\")\n    y, sr = librosa.load(file_path, sr=22050)\n    \n    # 1. MFCC\n    mfcc = librosa.feature.mfcc(y=y, sr=sr, n_mfcc=20)\n    mean_mfcc = np.mean(mfcc, axis=1)\n    std_mfcc = np.std(mfcc, axis=1)\n    \n    # 2. Spectral Contrast\n    contrast = librosa.feature.spectral_contrast(y=y, sr=sr, n_bands=6)\n    mean_contrast = np.mean(contrast, axis=1)\n    std_contrast = np.std(contrast, axis=1)\n    \n    # 3. Zero Crossing Rate\n    zcr = librosa.feature.zero_crossing_rate(y=y)\n    mean_zcr = np.mean(zcr, axis=1)\n    std_zcr = np.std(zcr, axis=1)\n    \n    # 4. Spectral Centroid\n    centroid = librosa.feature.spectral_centroid(y=y, sr=sr)\n    mean_centroid = np.mean(centroid, axis=1)\n    std_centroid = np.std(centroid, axis=1)\n    \n    # Concatenate all of them into a single 1-D feature vector\n    feature_vector = np.concatenate([\n        mean_mfcc, std_mfcc,\n        mean_contrast, std_contrast,\n        mean_zcr, std_zcr,\n        mean_centroid, std_centroid\n    ])\n    return feature_vector\n\ndef main():\n    # Find training files\n    speech_train_files = sorted(glob.glob('/workspace/train/speech/*.wav'))\n    music_train_files = sorted(glob.glob('/workspace/train/music/*.wav'))\n    \n    X_train = []\n    y_train = []\n    \n    print(\"Processing speech training files...\")\n    for f in speech_train_files:\n        feats = extract_features(f)\n        X_train.append(feats)\n        y_train.append('speech')\n        \n    print(\"Processing music training files...\")\n    for f in music_train_files:\n        feats = extract_features(f)\n        X_train.append(feats)\n        y_train.append('music')\n        \n    X_train = np.array(X_train)\n    y_train = np.array(y_train)\n    \n    print(f\"X_train shape: {X_train.shape}\")\n    \n    # Train Logistic Regression\n    # We can use standard scaling to normalize features if needed,\n    # but let's see how standard LogisticRegression performs.\n    # Actually, scaling is usually good for Logistic Regression since MFCC and Spectral Centroid\n    # have very different scales. Let's include StandardScaler to be safe and robust.\n    from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n    scaler = StandardScaler()\n    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)\n    \n    clf = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)\n    clf.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)\n    \n    # Find test files\n    test_files = sorted(glob.glob('/workspace/test/*.wav'))\n    \n    X_test = []\n    test_filenames = []\n    \n    print(\"Processing test files...\")\n    for f in test_files:\n        feats = extract_features(f)\n        X_test.append(feats)\n        test_filenames.append(os.path.basename(f))\n        \n    X_test = np.array(X_test)\n    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)\n    \n    # Predict\n    preds = clf.predict(X_test_scaled)\n    \n    # Write predictions\n    output_path = '/workspace/predictions.csv'\n    with open(output_path, 'w') as out_f:\n        out_f.write(\"filename,label\\n\")\n        for fname, label in zip(test_filenames, preds):\n            out_f.write(f\"{fname},{label}\\n\")\n            \n    print(f\"Predictions successfully written to {output_path}\")\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n"},"output":{"success":true},"callProviderMetadata":{"vertex":{"thoughtSignature":""}}}}
